Persona - College Student
William is a 22-year-old college junior located in Whitewater, Wisconsin. 
He spends his days working on his classes for architecture, and his nights working on 
projects for a long-term, unpaid internship with a local construction company. 
He was born in Vernon Hills, Illinois, to Jewish parents, where his father was an electrician, and 
his mother was an account executive. His younger sibling is diabetic, 
and helping care for them shaped how he views technology in his daily life. 

As a member of Gen Z, he knows enough of technology to get around basic safeguards,
but turns away from any inconvenience or extra hoops he might have to jump through. 
He is actively discussing his finances with his fiancée, and they are looking for a city they 
can both move to once they graduate. He is hoping his current finances can last him until then, 
and wants a better way to grasp his expenditure of money.

William's user stories:
As a user with limited income, I want to be able to plan for expenses ahead of time.
As a user dealing with a busy schedule, I want to set reminders for myself so the system notifies me when another payment needs to be made.
As a user with limited income and busy schedule during the semester, I want a clear budget on what I am allowed to spend to reach my overall goal.
As a user that doesn't like inconvinience or hoops when it comes to technology, I want an easy and simple to use system that won't stray me away.

User Scenario:
Late on a Friday night, William gets home tired from working at his internship. He doesn't want to manually enter 40 receipts,
so he goes to his bank site and exports his bank statement as a CSV file. He opens MindMyMint and clicks "import a file".
He finds his banks CSV file, and clicks okay. The python backend reads the file, it ignores the extra information and extracts "Date", "Description", "Ammount".
The system runs a script to try and clean up the data, turning several expenses to the category "groceries" and several others to "late night food".
He notices one expense is misattributed, so he double clicks it and renames the category. His map updates instantly. William sees
that his "late night food" expenses on a monthly view are almost as large as his "wedding savings". He clicks save and closes the app.
He texts his fiancee that they should eat in, rather than going out that night.

Requirements:
The system shall allow William to track all personal expenses and categorize spending automatically, providing a clear view of where his money goes each month. 
It shall generate simple, visual summaries that require minimal setup and interaction, helping him manage finances efficiently while balancing school, internship, and future relocation plans. 
The app shall be convenient, fast, and easy to use, avoiding unnecessary steps that might discourage regular use, and shall support shared visibility with his fiancée for joint financial planning.

